// =============================================================================

export const VERSE_LIFELINES: Record<string, { title: string; content: string; application: string[] }> = {
  "New Baby at Home": {
    title: "For New Parents",
    content: `Sleep-deprived and overwhelmed with joy—that's the paradox of new parenthood. Today's Scripture hits different when you're running on three hours of sleep and wondering if you're doing any of this right.

Here's what God wants you to know in this season: He isn't asking you to maintain your pre-baby spiritual routine. The devotional life that worked before—morning quiet times with hot coffee and a journal—might not be possible right now. And that's okay. God meets you where you are, not where you think you should be.

Today's verse isn't just for people with time to contemplate it. It's for you, exhausted parent, reading between diaper changes. It's for the 3am feeding when you're too tired to form coherent prayers. It's for the moment you lock yourself in the bathroom just to breathe. Scripture is alive and active—it doesn't require ideal circumstances to speak into your life.

This tiny human you're keeping alive? That's holy work. The patience you're learning, the selflessness you're developing, the love that surprises you with its fierceness—that's spiritual formation happening in real time. You're not failing at faith because your quiet times look different. You're living it out in the trenches.

God who spoke the universe into existence is present in your nursery right now. He's not disappointed that your prayers are mostly 'help me, Lord.' He's a Father. He understands exhaustion. He understands the weight of being responsible for a tiny life. Let today's verse remind you: you're not alone in this. You never were.`,
    application: [
      "Turn feedings and diaper changes into prayer moments. You don't need eloquent words—'Lord, give me patience' is communion with God.",
      "Put today's verse somewhere you'll see it repeatedly—on the changing table, taped to the formula container, on your bathroom mirror.",
      "Stop measuring your spiritual life by pre-baby standards. This is a different season with different fruit, and the Father knows what season you're in.",
      "Accept help without guilt. Letting others serve you isn't weakness—it's wisdom. You need rest to be present for your baby."
    ]
  },

  "Newly Married": {
    title: "For Newlyweds",
    content: `Marriage is beautiful—and harder than anyone told you it would be. The fairy tale didn't mention how difficult it is to merge two entire lives, two histories, two ways of loading the dishwasher. Today's Scripture speaks directly into this season of learning to become one.

Here's what you need to know: God's Word becomes an anchor when two imperfect people are trying to build something holy together. Your personal relationship with God doesn't compete with your marriage—it's actually what makes your marriage possible. The love, patience, and grace your spouse needs from you? You can't manufacture that from your own resources. It has to flow from somewhere deeper.

Today's verse isn't just for you individually—it's for both of you together. When you don't know how to resolve a conflict, Scripture provides wisdom. When you can't find the patience for one more conversation about finances, God's Word offers perspective. When you're wondering if you made a mistake, truth reminds you of the covenant you made.

The early years of marriage are full of small deaths—dying to selfishness, to your way being the only way, to the fantasy of who you thought your spouse would be. That's not failure; that's formation. Let Scripture shape how you navigate these deaths and resurrections.

Two people individually connected to God can build something stronger together than either could alone. Make the Word of God your shared foundation—the one thing you agree on when you agree on nothing else.`,
    application: [
      "Read Scripture together, even if it's just one verse over morning coffee. Building a shared spiritual life starts with small, consistent steps.",
      "When conflict heats up, pause. Return to today's verse before returning to the argument. What does it say about how you should respond?",
      "Pray for your spouse by name every day. It's hard to stay angry at someone you're interceding for before God.",
      "Identify where you've been expecting your spouse to be your spiritual source—to meet needs only God can meet. Release them from that impossible job."
    ]
  },

  "Starting a New Job": {
    title: "For Career Transitions",
    content: `New job energy is a cocktail of equal parts excitement and terror. You want to prove yourself, make a good first impression, show them they made the right choice hiring you. Imposter syndrome is probably already whispering that they'll figure out you don't belong. Today's Scripture offers grounding when everything feels uncertain.

Here's the truth: your identity doesn't flow from your job title—it never did, and it never will. The same God who opened this door will give you what you need to walk through it. You're not going into that new office alone. You're bringing with you everything Scripture says is true about who you are.

Today's verse isn't just devotional comfort—it's practical equipment for what you'll face. The stress of learning new systems, navigating office politics, proving your competence—all of that is real. But Scripture provides something your new employer can't: a foundation that doesn't shift based on performance reviews.

The skills that got you hired are real. The experience you bring is valuable. But your worth as a human being isn't up for evaluation. It was settled before you ever submitted a resume, in a different kind of transaction entirely. Let today's verse remind you of that settled identity before you walk through the new office doors.

Some of the most important work you'll do at this job won't show up on any performance review: integrity when no one's watching, kindness to the overlooked coworker, peace when everyone else is panicking. That's what it looks like to bring your faith to work.`,
    application: [
      "Before your first day, spend time in Scripture. Go into work filled with truth about who you are, not desperately seeking validation.",
      "When imposter syndrome hits, return to today's verse. What does God's Word say about your identity and worth?",
      "Look for one coworker you can pray for. Start building relationships that go deeper than professional networking.",
      "At the end of each day this week, ask God: 'Where did my faith show up at work today? Where did I forget who I am?'"
    ]
  },

  "Entering Retirement": {
    title: "For Those Retiring",
    content: `After decades of producing, achieving, building, and being defined by what you do, the work stops. The calendar that used to be packed is suddenly empty. A question you may not have faced since your twenties resurfaces: Who am I when I'm not working? Today's Scripture speaks into that disorienting space.

Here's what God wants you to know: your value was never in your productivity. That was always a lie the world sold you. Scripture has been true about your identity before you had a career, during your career, and now after it. You are God's beloved child. That hasn't changed and won't change.

Today's verse might mean something different now than it did when you were thirty and climbing. That's not because the verse changed—it's because you did. Decades of living have given you eyes to see depth you couldn't have seen before. This might be the richest season of Scripture engagement in your entire life, if you'll receive it.

You have time now. Time you always said you wanted for prayer, for study, for contemplation. The excuse of busyness is gone. What will you do with the space? The Word of God has been waiting for your undivided attention. The Father who has been patient through your career-focused years is ready to meet you in new ways.

And let's be clear: the world still needs you. The wisdom you've accumulated over decades of walking with God isn't meant to be hoarded. Younger believers need to see what long-term faith looks like. Your retirement isn't the end of your contribution—it might be the beginning of your most important one.`,
    application: [
      "Create intentional space for deep Scripture study—something the busyness of career years didn't allow. What book of the Bible have you always wanted to really dig into?",
      "Ask God what today's verse means for THIS season of life. The application at 65 is different than at 35. What new wisdom does He want to reveal?",
      "Find younger believers to share your journey with. Your decades of walking with God are a gift—don't hoard them.",
      "Resist the urge to fill every moment with activity. Stillness and contemplation are spiritual disciplines you can finally practice."
    ]
  },

  "Marriage Struggles": {
    title: "For the Struggling Marriage",
    content: `When marriage is hard—really hard, up-at-night hard—we usually focus on what our spouse isn't giving us. The list grows long: they don't listen, don't appreciate, don't understand, don't try. Today's Scripture speaks to something deeper than your spouse's failures.

Here's the uncomfortable truth: you can't pour out what hasn't been poured in. If you're running on empty spiritually, you have nothing to give your marriage except resentment and exhaustion. The disconnect in your marriage might be reflecting a deeper disconnect—from the Source who alone can give you what you're demanding from your spouse.

Today's verse isn't just nice words for a hard season. It's equipment. When you don't know what to say to your spouse, Scripture provides words. When you've run out of patience, the Word offers fresh supply. When you're convinced your situation is hopeless, truth reminds you of a God who specializes in resurrection.

This isn't about excusing your spouse's failures or minimizing real problems. Some marriages need professional help. Some situations involve abuse that requires immediate action. But for many struggling marriages, the path forward starts not with fixing your spouse but with your own return to the Source.

What if you approached today's conflict from a place of fullness instead of emptiness? What if you let God's Word shape your response before your hurt does? That's not ignoring the problem. It's approaching it from a completely different starting point.`,
    application: [
      "Before your next hard conversation with your spouse, spend time in today's verse. Go into it filled, not empty. Rooted, not reactive.",
      "Ask: What is God saying to ME through this Scripture—not what He's saying to my spouse. Focus on your own growth first.",
      "What are you demanding from your spouse that only God can actually provide? Identify it. Release them from that impossible expectation.",
      "Practice one act of love toward your spouse today—not to get something back, but simply because you've received from God."
    ]
  },

  "Going Through Divorce": {
    title: "For Those Facing Divorce",
    content: `Divorce feels like being ripped apart—because that's exactly what it is. Whatever the circumstances, whatever the reasons, this is one of the most painful experiences a person can endure. Today's Scripture meets you in the wreckage, not with platitudes, but with presence.

Here's what you need to know: God's Word remains true even when everything else is falling apart. The ground that's shaken beneath your feet isn't the only ground there is. There's a foundation that doesn't shift based on relationship status, that doesn't crumble when vows are broken, that holds even when you can't hold yourself.

Today's verse isn't a band-aid for a wound this deep. It won't make the pain disappear or answer the why questions that keep you up at night. But it offers something crucial: an anchor. Something solid to grab when everything else is in freefall.

You're going to need community to survive this. Not people who judge, not people who have easy answers, but people who will sit in the ashes with you. Let them. Grief shared is survivable. Grief alone can destroy you. The Scripture you're reading today was given in community, preserved by community, and is meant to be lived in community.

There will be days when you can't feel God at all. When the familiar words ring hollow and the prayers hit the ceiling. That's okay. Keep showing up anyway. The truth of Scripture doesn't depend on your ability to feel it. It remains true in the darkness, waiting for dawn.`,
    application: [
      "Don't isolate. Find one person—a counselor, a pastor, a trusted friend—who can walk through this with you. Isolation will make everything worse.",
      "Let today's verse be your anchor for TODAY. Don't try to figure out tomorrow. One verse, one day. That's enough right now.",
      "Grieve what was lost. Don't rush to 'move on.' But also don't let bitterness take root. Bitterness will poison everything it touches.",
      "When people ask how you're doing, tell the truth: 'I'm struggling, but I'm holding on to Scripture.' That testimony matters more than you know."
    ]
  },

  "Single Parenting": {
    title: "For Single Parents",
    content: `You're doing the work of two people—and feeling like you're failing at both. Between the morning routine and bedtime battles, work demands and homework help, trying to be everything while keeping food on the table... finding time for Scripture feels like one more impossible thing on an already impossible list.

Here's what you need to hear: God's Word isn't one more item on your to-do list. It's what makes everything else possible. The patience you need for the thousandth question? It comes from somewhere. The wisdom for impossible decisions? It has a source. Scripture isn't a burden for exhausted parents—it's fuel.

Today's verse doesn't require an hour of quiet contemplation to transform you. Five minutes of real engagement with God's Word beats zero minutes of idealized devotion that never happens. A verse on a sticky note on the bathroom mirror. A prayer app during your commute. Audio Bible while you make dinner. This is what Scripture looks like in your season—and it counts.

Your kids need to see you depend on God. That's discipleship in action. When they see you open the Bible in the hard moments, when they hear you pray honest prayers that aren't sanitized for children, when they watch you return to faith when life is brutal—that's the most powerful lesson you could ever teach them. You're not just a single parent. You're a demonstration of what it looks like to need God and find Him faithful.

The same God who sees the sparrow sees you in the chaos. He knows the weight you're carrying. He's not asking you to add more. He's offering to carry what you can't.`,
    application: [
      "Redefine 'quiet time' for this season. What's realistic—five minutes? Three verses? Scripture on audio during commute? Make it work for YOUR life.",
      "Read today's verse with your kids, even if they're young. Their questions might teach you something. Your need for God disciplines them.",
      "Accept help without guilt. 'I can do it myself' isn't faith—it's exhausting pride. Who can you let in this week?",
      "When you feel like you're failing, remember: a parent who keeps showing up, keeps depending on God, keeps trying—that's not failure. That's faithfulness."
    ]
  },

  "Wayward Child": {
    title: "For Parents of Prodigals",
    content: `Nothing breaks a parent's heart like watching a child walk away—from you, from faith, from everything you tried to teach them. You did everything you were supposed to do: church, youth group, bedtime prayers, Bible stories. And somehow they're still in the far country, making choices that terrify you. Today's Scripture meets you in that specific grief.

Here's the hardest truth: you cannot make your child come back to faith. That's not your job. You can't control their choices, their beliefs, their path. What you CAN control is what you do while they're gone—and that matters more than you know.

Today's verse is for YOU, not ammunition to send to your child. They don't need more Scripture texts from you right now. They've heard the message their whole life. What they need to see is the message lived—in you. A parent who stays rooted when life is hard. A faith that's real enough to sustain you through heartbreak. Evidence that what you believe actually works.

Remember the prodigal son story? The father didn't chase his son to the pig farm. He didn't send guilt trips or manipulative letters. He stayed home. He kept the light on. He watched the road with hope. And when the son came to his senses, he knew exactly where to go because home hadn't changed.

Your abiding in Scripture right now—working today's verse into your broken heart—might be the lifeline your child eventually follows home. Stay rooted. Stay faithful. Keep the light on.`,
    application: [
      "Don't let your child's choices disconnect YOU from God's Word. Your grief needs somewhere to go. Process it with Scripture, not just anxiety.",
      "Pray today's verse over your child, but resist the urge to preach it at them. They know what you believe. Now they need to see you live it.",
      "Keep the relationship open as much as safely possible. Prodigals need to know the way home isn't blocked by your disappointment.",
      "Find other parents of prodigals to journey with. You need people who understand this specific grief. You weren't meant to carry it alone."
    ]
  },

  "Infertility Journey": {
    title: "For Those Facing Infertility",
    content: `Month after month of hoping, praying, waiting, and being disappointed. Baby announcements on social media feel like personal attacks. Baby showers require emotional armor. Well-meaning friends offer advice that makes you want to scream. Today's Scripture meets you in that specific, isolating pain.

Here's something the church often gets wrong: your worth as a person is not determined by your fertility. Whatever today's verse is about, it's not about childbearing being the measure of a blessed life. You are fully valuable, fully loved, fully seen—right now, in this painful waiting.

But let's also acknowledge: infertility is profound grief. The monthly disappointment, the hormonal rollercoaster, the invasive procedures, the questions from family—it's exhausting on every level. Scripture doesn't minimize that. The Psalms are full of raw anguish. Hannah wept bitterly before the Lord. Rachel cried out in pain. You're in biblical company.

Today's verse enters your grief, not to fix it or explain it, but to meet you in it. The God who inspired these words sees you—in the fertility clinic waiting room, in the bathroom crying over another negative test, in the baby shower you're forcing yourself to attend. He's not distant from your pain. He's present in it.

Whatever happens—whether children come through biology, adoption, or some path you haven't yet discovered—your story isn't over. Today's verse is part of a larger story that God is still writing. Stay in the Story, even when this chapter hurts.`,
    application: [
      "Grieve honestly. The Psalms of lament give you words when you have none. Bring your raw emotions to God—He can handle them.",
      "Give yourself permission to protect your heart. Skip the baby shower if you need to. Mute the pregnancy announcements. That's not bitterness—it's wisdom.",
      "Find community with others who understand this specific pain. Infertility is isolating. You don't have to walk it alone.",
      "Ask God what He IS doing in your life right now. Not as replacement for what you want—but alongside it. What fruit is growing in this painful soil?"
    ]
  },

  "Blended Family": {
    title: "For Blended Families",
    content: `Yours, mine, ours—and complexity that nobody warned you about. Step-parents and step-kids, ex-spouses and custody schedules, trying to build unity while navigating land mines of loyalty and resentment. Today's Scripture speaks into this slow, painful, beautiful process of becoming family.

Here's the truth: blended families don't blend easily, no matter what anyone told you. What feels like friction—the resistance, the 'you're not my real parent,' the complicated holidays—is actually two family systems learning to grow together. That takes years, not months. It takes grace that you don't naturally have.

Today's verse isn't just for biological families living in simple situations. The God who inspired Scripture sees your complicated dinner table. He understands loyalty conflicts and custody arrangements. He knows that 'love your neighbor' is hardest when your neighbor is your step-child or your ex-spouse.

What your blended family needs most is adults who are individually rooted in God's Word. When you're filled with Scripture, you have patience for the step-child who's testing you. When today's verse has soaked into you, you have grace for situations that don't feel fair. You can't force family unity—but you can model what it looks like to be shaped by Scripture even when life is complicated.

This family you're building is different, not deficient. The grace required to make it work, the forgiveness demanded every day, the love that has to be chosen again and again—that's holy work. Today's verse is fuel for that work.`,
    application: [
      "Lower your timeline expectations. Blending takes years, not months. What feels like failure might just be normal pace. Keep applying Scripture consistently.",
      "Pray for each family member by name—including the ones who frustrate you most, including the ex. Let God's Word shape how you see them.",
      "Create new traditions that belong to THIS family. You're not erasing the past—you're building something new that Scripture can shape.",
      "Find other blended families to learn from. You need people who understand that 'it's complicated' is an understatement."
    ]
  },

  "Caring for Aging Parents": {
    title: "For Caregivers of Aging Parents",
    content: `The role reversal is disorienting. You're now making decisions for the person who used to make decisions for you. Handling medications, navigating medical appointments, having conversations about end-of-life care with someone who changed your diapers. Today's Scripture meets you in that exhausting, honoring, heartbreaking work.

Here's what you need to know: caregiver burnout is real, and it's not a sign of weak faith. You cannot pour out indefinitely from an empty vessel. If today's verse is going to sustain you through this marathon, you have to actually engage with it—not just add it to the list of things you feel guilty about not doing.

Scripture isn't another burden for the already-burdened. It's oxygen. The patience you need for repeated questions, the grace for difficult behaviors, the wisdom for impossible decisions—you don't manufacture that from your own reserves. It comes from somewhere outside you, and it's offered in God's Word.

The person you're caring for used to care for you. They taught you to walk, wiped your tears, sat with you when you were sick. What you're doing now—the midnight medicine runs, the patience with confusion, the showing up day after day—this is love embodied. It's honoring your father and mother in the hardest possible way.

Today's verse sees you. The God who inspired it sees the sacrifice you're making. He knows you're tired. He knows you feel guilty when you're frustrated. He knows this wasn't in your ten-year plan. And He meets you here, in the exhaustion, with the specific sustenance you need.`,
    application: [
      "Schedule respite, and don't feel guilty about it. You cannot sustain caregiving without breaks. Time in Scripture requires energy to focus.",
      "Let today's verse remind you why this matters. What you're doing is holy work. Exhausting, yes—but holy.",
      "Accept help from others. You weren't meant to do this alone. Who can you ask to sit with your parent so you can rest and reconnect with God?",
      "Grieve the parent you're losing, even while they're still here. That anticipatory grief is real. Bring it to God—He understands loss."
    ]
  },

  "Empty Nest": {
    title: "For Empty Nesters",
    content: `The house is quiet. Too quiet. The rooms that used to echo with noise and activity now sit empty. For years—decades maybe—your identity was wrapped up in being needed. Mom. Dad. The one who drove carpool and made meals and helped with homework. And now? The need is gone. Today's Scripture speaks into that disorienting silence.

Here's what God wants you to know: your value was never in what you produced. Being needed felt good, but it wasn't your identity—it was a season. Scripture has been true about who you are before the kids came, while they were growing, and now that they've launched. You are God's beloved. That hasn't changed.

Today's verse might hit differently in an empty house. Without the chaos of family life, you have space to actually hear it. Without the constant demands, you can contemplate it. This is an invitation, not a loss. The spiritual growth that got crowded out by soccer schedules and homework help has room to flourish now.

But let's also acknowledge: the transition hurts. You might need to grieve what's gone before you can embrace what's coming. That's okay. Scripture doesn't rush you. God understands that endings are hard, even good endings, even necessary endings. Let today's verse meet you in the grief as well as the possibility.

Your kids still need you—just differently. They need a parent who models what long-term faith looks like. They need a home to come back to that's full of peace and purpose, not emptiness. What you do in this quiet house, how you fill this quiet time, shapes what they see when they visit.`,
    application: [
      "Grieve the transition fully. Don't rush to fill the space with busyness. Acknowledge what's lost before embracing what's coming.",
      "Create new rhythms of engaging Scripture. What works now that the chaos is gone? Longer mornings? Study groups? Things that weren't possible before.",
      "Ask God what today's verse means for THIS season. The application at fifty-five is different than at thirty-five. What new depth is available?",
      "Stay connected to your adult children without smothering them. Let them see you thriving, growing, finding new purpose rooted in God's Word."
    ]
  },

  "Fighting Cancer": {
    title: "For Those Fighting Cancer",
    content: `The diagnosis changed everything. Life divides into before and after. Suddenly you're learning vocabulary you never wanted to know, navigating a medical system designed to overwhelm, facing your mortality in ways most people spend their whole lives avoiding. Today's Scripture enters that upended world.

Here's what the God of Scripture wants you to know: He doesn't promise to remove this trial. He doesn't promise healing on your timeline or in the way you want. But He promises presence. He promises that His Word is true in the chemo chair, in the waiting room, in the 3am fear, in the uncertainty about what comes next.

Today's verse isn't a guarantee of outcome. It's equipment for the journey—whatever that journey looks like. When you're too exhausted to pray elaborate prayers, Scripture gives you words. When your thoughts spiral to worst-case scenarios, truth offers a different storyline. When well-meaning people say things that make you want to scream, the Word offers what they can't.

Some of the most profound engagement with Scripture happens in hospital rooms. When everything else is stripped away—work, hobbies, the busyness that usually distracts—what remains is what matters. You have an opportunity, in this terrible season, for depth with God that the healthy and distracted never experience. Not a silver lining that makes cancer worth it—nothing makes cancer worth it—but a gift hidden in the wreckage.

You may not have energy for long Bible studies or deep theological exploration. That's okay. One verse. Today's verse. Held and returned to and wrestled with. That's enough. That's more than enough.`,
    application: [
      "Let people help. Now is not the time for independence. Accept meals, accept visits, accept prayers. You need the support.",
      "When you can't pray words, breathe Scripture. One phrase from today's verse. Inhale 'Lord,' exhale 'help.' That's communion with God.",
      "Don't waste precious energy on 'why.' You may never get an answer. Focus on 'who'—Who is with you in this valley.",
      "Your witness matters. How you walk through this—clinging to Scripture—impacts everyone watching. Not perfectly. Honestly. That's the testimony."
    ]
  },

  "Supporting Someone Sick": {
    title: "For Those Supporting the Sick",
    content: `Watching someone you love suffer is its own kind of pain. You feel helpless—and you are. You want to fix it, heal it, make it better. But you can't. Today's Scripture meets you in that helplessness.

Here's the truth: you're not the healer. That's not your job. Today's verse isn't a magic formula to make your loved one well. Scripture doesn't work that way. But it does offer something you desperately need: a foundation to stand on when everything else is shaking.

Your job isn't to have answers. Your job is to be present. To show up consistently, even when you don't know what to say. To sit in silence when words fail. To bring meals and run errands and be a steady presence in chaos. That's love embodied. That's what Scripture talks about when it talks about loving your neighbor.

But here's what you might not want to hear: you can't sustain this if you're running on empty. Compassion fatigue is real. If you're pouring out without being poured into, you'll burn out—and then you won't be any help to anyone. Today's verse isn't just for them. It's for you. You need Scripture to sustain you so you can sustain them.

The same God who sees your loved one's suffering sees yours. He knows the long hours, the difficult conversations, the grief of watching someone you love fade. He meets you in your helplessness, not with formulas, but with presence. With His Word. With Himself.`,
    application: [
      "Show up consistently, even when you don't know what to say. Your presence matters more than your words. Don't wait until you have something profound.",
      "Protect your own time in Scripture. You need it. You're not abandoning your loved one by caring for your own soul. You're making sure you can keep showing up.",
      "Pray WITH your loved one, not just for them. Read today's verse together. Let them hear you engage with God about their situation.",
      "Accept your limits. You can't be everything, fix everything, or be there every moment. That's not failure—that's being human."
    ]
  },

  "Chronic Illness": {
    title: "For Those with Chronic Illness",
    content: `It's not going away. That's the hardest part of chronic illness—the forever-ness of it. Acute illness has an end. Chronic illness is a constant companion, a daily negotiation, a permanent adjustment to the life you thought you'd have. Today's Scripture enters that ongoing reality.

Here's what God knows about you: your limits. He isn't comparing your engagement with today's verse to what healthy people can do. He isn't disappointed that you can't maintain the spiritual disciplines you used to. He sees what you're working with—the pain, the fatigue, the brain fog, the daily battles—and He meets you there.

Scripture doesn't require physical health to transform you. Some of the deepest engagement with God's Word happens in broken bodies. When you can't distract yourself with busyness and productivity, when illness strips away everything but the essential, you have opportunity for depth that the healthy and distracted rarely experience.

What looks like a small spiritual effort to others might be an enormous victory given what you're carrying. Getting through the day with grace—that counts. Managing pain without letting it make you bitter—that's spiritual formation. Maintaining faith when your body is failing—that's extraordinary faithfulness.

Today's verse isn't mocking you with standards you can't reach. It's meeting you on the bed, in the doctor's office, in the hard days. The God who inspired Scripture knows exactly what you're facing. He wrote His Word for people with bodies that fail—because that's all of us, eventually.`,
    application: [
      "Adjust your expectations of yourself. What does engaging Scripture look like given your actual limits, not the limits you wish you had?",
      "On bad days, one verse is enough. Holding today's Scripture in your mind as you rest—that counts. That's faithfulness.",
      "Find community that understands. Chronic illness is isolating. You need people who get it, who won't offer platitudes.",
      "Let your journey encourage others. Your perseverance matters. People are watching. Your witness from the hard place has unique power."
    ]
  },

  "Grieving a Death": {
    title: "For the Grieving",
    content: `Grief makes everything feel distant—God included. The person you lost is gone, and sometimes it feels like joy, hope, and faith have left with them. Today's Scripture enters the fog.

Here's what you need to know: you don't have to feel close to God for His Word to be true. Grief often creates a strange numbness where the familiar feels foreign, where words that used to comfort now ring hollow. That's normal. That's grief. It doesn't mean you've lost your faith. It means you've lost someone you loved.

Today's verse isn't demanding that you feel better or process faster. Scripture allows for grief. Lament fills the Psalms. Jesus wept at the tomb of His friend. There's no timeline on mourning, despite what well-meaning people might suggest. God's Word meets you in the darkness without demanding you hurry into the light.

The relationship you had with Scripture before this loss might feel different now. That's okay. You're different. Grief changes us. But the truth of God's Word hasn't changed. It waits patiently for you to return to it, however slowly, however gradually, however tentatively.

Give yourself permission to not be okay. Give yourself permission to engage Scripture differently for a while—maybe just sitting with one verse rather than completing a reading plan. The important thing isn't the quantity of your engagement. It's staying connected, even loosely, even numbly, while the grief does its work.`,
    application: [
      "Give yourself permission to not produce spiritually right now. Grief is exhausting work. Simply holding today's verse is enough.",
      "Don't isolate. Grief shared with community is survivable. Grief alone is crushing. Let others in, even when it's hard.",
      "When you can't feel God, keep showing up anyway. Read today's verse even if it's hollow. Presence during numbness is faithfulness.",
      "Remember: Jesus wept. Your tears are not a failure of faith. The God who inspired Scripture understands grief from the inside."
    ]
  },

  "Miscarriage or Loss of Child": {
    title: "For Those Who've Lost a Child",
    content: `There are no words for this grief. The loss of a child—whether through miscarriage, stillbirth, or at any age—is the most unnatural suffering a parent can endure. Today's Scripture doesn't try to explain or fix or minimize. It enters the darkness.

Your child was real. Whether you held them for years or never got to hold them at all, the loss is profound and legitimate. Don't let anyone minimize it with platitudes about heaven or God's plan. This is devastating, and Scripture gives you permission to be devastated.

Today's verse isn't a bandage for this wound. Nothing heals it—not really. But Scripture offers something crucial: a God who understands. The Father watched His own Son die. He knows this specific grief. He's not distant from your pain. He's in it.

You will never 'get over' this loss. But you can get through it. Today's verse is one small piece of equipment for the journey—not a cure, but a companion. The God who inspired Scripture walks with you through the valley. He doesn't explain it. He doesn't justify it. He's just there.

The community of faith holds your pain with you. Not with answers—there aren't any. But with presence. With meals and silence and permission to not be okay. The Scripture we share was given to be lived in community, especially in the hardest moments.`,
    application: [
      "Grieve fully and without apology. Don't let anyone rush you, minimize your loss, or tell you how to feel. This is real and profound loss.",
      "Name your child if you haven't. Acknowledge what was lost. This was a real person you're mourning, however brief their life.",
      "Find others who understand—support groups, counselors who specialize in this loss, parents who've walked this road.",
      "When you're ready, return to Scripture slowly. The God who meets you in today's verse is the God of resurrection. This isn't the end."
    ]
  },

  "Depression": {
    title: "For Those with Depression",
    content: `Depression lies. It tells you you're alone, you're worthless, you're a burden. It tells you nothing matters—including this verse. Today's Scripture tells you the truth: you're not what depression says you are.

Here's what you need to hear: depression isn't a faith failure. It's not punishment for sin or evidence of weak belief. Depression is often a chemical reality in the brain, sometimes triggered by circumstances, always devastating. You wouldn't tell a diabetic to just pray more. The same grace applies here.

Today's verse might feel hollow. That's okay. Depression has a way of draining meaning from everything—including the things that used to matter. The truth of Scripture doesn't depend on your ability to feel it. It remains true in the darkness, waiting for dawn. Your job isn't to feel transformed by today's verse. It's just to read it. To let the words land somewhere, even if you can't feel where.

Engaging Scripture when you're depressed is an act of defiance. It's choosing to show up even when everything in you says there's no point. That's not weakness. That's remarkable courage. And it counts—every verse read when you didn't want to, every prayer groaned when words failed, every step toward God when you could barely move.

God sees you in the darkness. The One who inspired Scripture is not distant from your depression. He's present in it, working in ways you can't perceive. Trust the process even when you can't feel the progress.`,
    application: [
      "Today's only goal: read this verse. That's enough. Don't measure your spiritual life by what healthy people can do.",
      "Seeking professional help is wisdom, not weakness. Medication can be grace. Therapy can be healing. Scripture doesn't prohibit doctors.",
      "Tell someone how you're really doing. Depression thrives in isolation. Breaking the silence is an act of faith.",
      "When you can't feel God, remember: feelings aren't facts. The truth of Scripture remains true even when depression makes everything feel hopeless."
    ]
  },

  "Anxiety & Worry": {
    title: "For the Anxious",
    content: `Anxiety lies too—differently than depression, but just as persistently. It tells you everything depends on you. If you don't worry about it, who will? If you don't prepare for every disaster, something terrible will happen. Today's Scripture offers a different voice.

Here's the truth: you weren't designed to carry what you're carrying. The weight of managing the future, controlling outcomes, preparing for every contingency—that was never your job. Anxiety has convinced you that constant vigilance is your responsibility. Scripture says otherwise.

Today's verse isn't telling you to stop caring about things that matter. It's telling you that Someone else is ultimately in charge. Your worry doesn't prevent disasters. Your anxiety doesn't keep your loved ones safe. The world turns without your management, and the God who inspired Scripture is sovereign over all of it.

This doesn't mean anxiety is easy to overcome. It's not a willpower problem. It might be chemical, might be situational, might need professional help. But engaging Scripture offers something medication can't: a different story to live in. A story where you're not responsible for everything. A story where Someone stronger holds what you can't.

Today's verse is an invitation to lay down the weight. Not all at once—anxiety doesn't release that easily. But repeatedly, intentionally, bringing your worries to the Word and leaving them there. Again and again and again.`,
    application: [
      "Write down your top three worries. For each one, ask: 'Is this ultimately my responsibility, or God's?' Begin releasing what isn't yours.",
      "When anxiety spikes, return to today's verse. Read it slowly. Let it interrupt the spiral. Use it like medicine.",
      "Consider whether you need professional help. Therapy and medication can work alongside Scripture, not against it.",
      "Practice a breath prayer with today's verse. Inhale one phrase, exhale another. Let Scripture regulate your nervous system."
    ]
  },

  "Loneliness & Isolation": {
    title: "For the Lonely",
    content: `Loneliness is an epidemic, and it doesn't discriminate. You can feel lonely in a crowd. Lonely in a marriage. Lonely in a church full of people. Today's Scripture meets you in that ache.

Here's the first truth: even when you feel utterly alone, God is present. Scripture was given by a God who promises to never leave or forsake you. Today's verse comes from that God, and reading it is an act of connection with Him. You're not as alone as you feel.

But here's the second truth: Scripture was given in community, for community. The Word of God assumes we won't live isolated lives. The 'one anothers' of the New Testament require others to practice. Today's verse is meant to be lived with people, not just read in solitude.

Loneliness might be telling you something important: you've pulled away from community, or you haven't yet found the community you need. Scripture doesn't promise that God-and-me is enough. It points you toward God-and-us. Vertical connection with God and horizontal connection with others.

Don't wait for community to find you. Lonely people have to be brave. Reach out. Show up. Join something. It will be awkward—that's normal. But isolation is slowly killing you. You were designed for connection, and today's verse is inviting you back toward it.`,
    application: [
      "Reach out to ONE person this week. Send a text, make a call. Small steps break the isolation. You have to take the first one.",
      "Join a community group or Bible study. Studying Scripture with others is different than studying alone. You need both, but especially the with-others.",
      "When loneliness hits, talk to God honestly: 'I feel so alone right now. But I know Your Word says You're here.' Let His presence meet you.",
      "Be honest with someone about how you're feeling. 'I've been struggling with loneliness' opens doors. You might be surprised who feels the same."
    ]
  },

  "Burnout & Exhaustion": {
    title: "For the Exhausted",
    content: `You're running on empty and you've been running on empty for a while. The to-do list never ends. The demands never stop. You're tired in a way sleep doesn't fix—soul-tired, bone-tired, tired of being tired. Today's Scripture meets you in the depletion.

Here's the hard truth: your exhaustion might be evidence that something's broken in how you're living. You've been trying to produce, achieve, perform—and you've been running on your own fuel instead of receiving from the Source. Burnout is what happens when you live like everything depends on you.

Today's verse isn't another item on your to-do list. It's not 'one more thing' demanding your depleted energy. Scripture is meant to fill you, not drain you. If engaging with God's Word feels like another burden, you're approaching it wrong—or you're too burned out to approach anything right.

What you need isn't more productivity tips or better time management. You need to stop. To receive. To let yourself be filled before you try to pour out again. Today's verse is an invitation to slow down long enough to actually receive something—to be ministered to rather than ministry.

The God who inspired Scripture isn't impressed by your hustle. He's concerned about your depletion. He's been trying to get your attention. Maybe burnout is finally loud enough to make you listen.`,
    application: [
      "Before doing anything productive tomorrow, read today's verse slowly. Don't rush to application. Just receive it.",
      "Identify one commitment that's draining you unnecessarily. What would happen if you let it go? Give yourself permission to consider it.",
      "Schedule actual rest. Not 'productive rest'—actual rest. Sabbath wasn't a suggestion. Your body, mind, and soul need it.",
      "Ask yourself honestly: What am I trying to prove? Who am I trying to impress? What's driving the exhaustion? Let Scripture speak to those answers."
    ]
  },

  "Addiction Struggle": {
    title: "For Those Battling Addiction",
    content: `Addiction promises what it can't deliver. Relief, escape, comfort, control—it whispers that this time will be different, this time will be enough, this time won't cost so much. It's a lie every time. Today's Scripture offers something different.

Here's the truth: the pull toward addiction often comes strongest when you're empty—when you need something to fill the void, numb the pain, manage the unmanageable. The substance or behavior becomes a substitute source of life. But there are no substitutes. Only counterfeits.

Today's verse points to a different Source. The God who inspired Scripture offers real filling, real comfort, real peace—not the temporary relief that addiction provides, followed by deeper emptiness. But engaging Scripture isn't a magic formula that makes cravings disappear. Recovery is harder than that.

You cannot do this alone. That's not weakness; that's wisdom. Addiction thrives in isolation. Recovery happens in community. Today's verse was given in the context of community, and it's meant to be lived in community. The people who find freedom find it together with others who understand the battle.

Every day clean is a victory. Every time you choose Scripture over the substance is a win. Every step toward recovery—even if you relapse, even if you fall, even if you're starting over for the hundredth time—matters. The God who inspired today's verse doesn't give up on you. Neither should you.`,
    application: [
      "When cravings hit, read today's verse out loud. Let it interrupt the pattern. Use Scripture like a tool, not just a devotional.",
      "Get into recovery community. AA, Celebrate Recovery, whatever works—you cannot do this alone. Find people who understand the battle.",
      "One day at a time. Today's only question: Will I stay connected to God today? That's enough. Tomorrow is tomorrow.",
      "Be honest with one person about your struggle. Secrets keep addiction alive. Confession in safe community brings freedom."
    ]
  },

  "Job Loss": {
    title: "For Those Who've Lost Jobs",
    content: `Losing your job can feel like losing yourself. The routine, the purpose, the identity, the paycheck—all gone at once. You are more than your job title, but it might not feel that way right now. Today's Scripture meets you in that disorientation.

Here's the truth: your identity doesn't flow from employment. It never did—even though our culture told you otherwise. The same God who gave you skills and abilities and achievements is still that God today. What you brought to that job came from somewhere, and that somewhere hasn't changed.

Today's verse is about who you are, not what you do. In a season when what-you-do has been taken away, let who-you-are come into focus. Scripture has always said your worth comes from being made in God's image, being known by Him, being loved by Him. That hasn't changed with your employment status.

This waiting season isn't wasted. You have time now—time you didn't have when work consumed you. Time to read Scripture without rushing, to pray without watching the clock, to reconnect with the God who gets crowded out by busy careers. Let this terrible season produce something good in you.

The next thing will come. In the meantime, let today's verse remind you who you are when the job title is gone.`,
    application: [
      "Each morning, before job searching, read today's verse. Let Scripture define your identity before the job boards try to.",
      "Make a list of the gifts, skills, and experiences you brought to your previous role. Remember: those came from somewhere, and they're still with you.",
      "Stay connected to community. Job loss makes people want to hide. Don't isolate. Let others encourage you and support you.",
      "Ask God what He might be doing in this season. What has He been waiting to teach you? What growth does this hard space allow?"
    ]
  },

  "Financial Crisis": {
    title: "For Those in Financial Crisis",
    content: `Money stress is all-consuming. It's hard to think about anything else when you don't know how you'll pay the bills, make rent, feed your family. Anxiety follows you everywhere. Today's Scripture enters that consuming worry.

Here's the truth: financial crisis often exposes where we've been placing our trust. Not as judgment—we all trust money too much in this culture—but as revelation. The security that felt solid was always more fragile than we admitted. Scripture has been trying to tell us this all along.

Today's verse is about trusting a different Source. Not because the bills will magically disappear or because faith replaces action. You still need to budget, look for work, seek help, make hard choices. But underneath all that activity, Scripture offers a foundation that isn't made of dollars.

The God who inspired today's verse promises to provide for His people. Not always the way we expect, not always at the pace we want, but what we actually need. That's not prosperity gospel promising wealth. That's shepherd language promising provision—daily bread, one day at a time.

What would it look like to face the financial crisis from a place of trust rather than panic? Not ignoring the numbers, but approaching them differently—with Scripture as your foundation instead of your last resort.`,
    application: [
      "Bring your finances to God with brutal honesty. No hiding, no sanitizing. He already knows the numbers. Let today's verse meet you there.",
      "Reach out for help. Church benevolence funds, community resources, financial counseling. Asking for help is wisdom, not shame.",
      "Look for what this crisis might be teaching you. Not as punishment—but what growth is happening in the hard place?",
      "Practice generosity even now, even small amounts. It sounds crazy, but it breaks the scarcity mindset and connects you to God's provision."
    ]
  },

  "Toxic Work Environment": {
    title: "For Those in Toxic Workplaces",
    content: `Eight hours a day—or more—in a soul-crushing environment. The politics, the manipulation, the impossible demands, the values that conflict with everything you believe. It takes a toll that follows you home. Today's Scripture meets you in that hostile territory.

Here's the truth: your workplace doesn't determine your character—but it does test it. The integrity you maintain when no one's watching, the kindness you show to people who don't deserve it, the peace you hold when everyone else is panicking—that's what happens when Scripture shapes a life, even in a toxic environment.

Today's verse doesn't promise to make your workplace better. Some environments stay toxic no matter how you respond. But Scripture shapes how you navigate the toxicity—whether that means enduring with grace or recognizing it's time to leave.

Daniel in Babylon. Joseph in Egypt. Esther in Persia. Scripture is full of people who lived faithfully in hostile environments. They weren't naive about the toxicity. They just didn't let it define them. Their identity came from somewhere deeper, and that deeper identity shaped how they showed up.

You carry today's verse into that office with you. The God who inspired Scripture goes with you into the meetings, the conflicts, the draining interactions. You're not alone there—even though it often feels that way.`,
    application: [
      "Before work each day, read today's verse. Go in filled with Scripture, not empty and defensive.",
      "Look for one person in that environment who needs encouragement. Be the presence of Christ to them, even if no one else notices.",
      "Protect your time in Scripture fiercely. The toxicity will drain you if you don't have a source of refilling.",
      "Pray about whether to stay or go. Both can be faithful choices. Make the decision connected to God, not running from pain."
    ]
  },

  "Career Uncertainty": {
    title: "For Those Facing Career Uncertainty",
    content: `You don't know what you want to do with your life—or maybe what you were doing isn't working anymore. The path that seemed clear has gotten fuzzy. Today's Scripture enters that confusion.

Here's the truth: God isn't anxious about your career. He knows the path forward, even when you don't. Today's verse comes from a God who sees around corners you can't see around. Your job isn't to have it all figured out. Your job is to take the next faithful step.

Scripture doesn't usually provide career counseling in the traditional sense. It doesn't tell you whether to take this job or that one, pursue this path or another. But it shapes the kind of person who makes those decisions. It provides values, priorities, wisdom. The career clarity you're seeking might emerge not from analyzing options but from being shaped by the Word.

Clarity often comes THROUGH faithfulness, not before it. The person who waits for perfect certainty before moving stays stuck forever. Take the next step you can see. Be faithful in small things. Let today's verse shape how you approach the uncertainty—not with anxiety but with trust.

The same God who gave you gifts and abilities is still working in your life. The passion He's placed in you isn't random. The experiences that have shaped you aren't wasted. He's not done with your story—even though you can't see how this chapter ends.`,
    application: [
      "Replace 'What should I do with my life?' with 'What does today's verse call me to be?' Identity questions before career questions.",
      "Take the next faithful step you CAN see, even if the destination is unclear. Action often produces clarity that contemplation can't.",
      "Talk to wise believers who've navigated career transitions. How did faithfulness lead to clarity for them?",
      "What energizes you? What are you good at? What needs exist around you? Often calling emerges at the intersection—as you stay faithful to Scripture."
    ]
  },

  "Doubting My Faith": {
    title: "For Those Doubting",
    content: `Doubt feels dangerous—like you're one question away from the whole thing falling apart. The beliefs you've held your whole life suddenly have cracks. Today's Scripture meets you in that shaky place.

Here's the truth: doubt can be a sign of faith that's growing up. Childish faith accepts everything without question. Mature faith wrestles, questions, pushes back—and often emerges stronger. The God who inspired Scripture isn't threatened by your doubts. He's big enough to handle your hardest questions.

Today's verse doesn't require certainty to transform you. You don't have to have all the answers to engage with God's Word. Scripture has been transforming doubters for millennia—people like Thomas, who needed to touch the wounds before he believed.

The key is to doubt while staying connected. Don't pull away from Scripture because it feels uncomfortable. Don't isolate while you're questioning. Bring your doubts to the Word, to trusted believers, to the community of faith. Doubt processed in connection leads to deeper faith. Doubt processed alone leads to drifting.

Keep reading, even when the words feel uncertain. Keep showing up, even when you're not sure what you believe. The same Scripture you're questioning is patient enough to wait for your questions to resolve.`,
    application: [
      "Bring your doubts to God directly: 'Lord, I believe. Help my unbelief.' That's honest faith. He's not offended by your questions.",
      "Find a wise believer who won't shame your doubts but will process them with you. Doubt needs conversation, not isolation.",
      "Keep showing up. Read today's verse even when it raises more questions. Faith is a choice, not just a feeling.",
      "Study what's specifically troubling you. Often doubt is about particular issues, not faith as a whole. Name the questions specifically."
    ]
  },

  "Feeling Far from God": {
    title: "For the Distant",
    content: `You've drifted and you know it. Maybe life got busy and Scripture got squeezed out. Maybe pain pushed you away. Maybe you don't even know how it happened—you just woke up one day and God felt far. Today's verse is an invitation back.

Here's the truth: God hasn't moved. The distance you feel isn't evidence of His absence. Scripture was true when you felt close, and it's still true now. The Word hasn't changed—you have. But here's the good news: you can come back.

Today's verse isn't demanding penance or perfection. Scripture offers grace for exactly this moment—the moment when you realize you've drifted and want to return. You don't have to earn your way back. You don't have to clean yourself up first. You just start. You read the verse. You take one step back toward the God who never stopped waiting.

Stop trying to feel your way back. You might not feel close to God for a while—that's normal after a drift. Feelings follow actions. Start reading Scripture again, start praying again, start showing up again—and trust that the feelings will eventually follow.

The same Scripture you're reading today was waiting for you to come back. It's patient like that. God is patient like that. The drift is over whenever you want it to be over. Today could be that day.`,
    application: [
      "Stop waiting to feel ready. Start reading Scripture again today. Just start. Feelings follow actions.",
      "Start small. Today's verse is enough. Don't try to recreate what you had. Just take one step back toward God.",
      "Don't add shame to distance. God isn't disappointed in you. He's glad you're coming back. Receive grace.",
      "Tell one person that you've been distant and you're trying to return. Let someone else know what you're doing. Accountability helps."
    ]
  },

  "Unanswered Prayer": {
    title: "For Those with Unanswered Prayers",
    content: `You've been praying. And praying. And praying. And nothing has changed. You did everything you were supposed to do—asked in faith, believed, persisted—and God seems silent. Today's Scripture feels hollow when you've been faithful and nothing's happened.

Here's the truth: unanswered prayer isn't evidence that you're doing it wrong. It's not proof that God doesn't care or that Scripture is empty. Sometimes prayers take longer than we want. Sometimes the answer is 'not yet.' Sometimes it's 'something different.' Sometimes we don't get to understand until we see Him face to face.

Today's verse isn't a formula that guarantees outcomes. Scripture promises that God hears, that prayer matters, that our requests reach Him. It doesn't promise every request will be granted on our timeline. That's not how a relationship with an infinite God works.

Keep praying. Keep reading Scripture. But hold outcomes loosely. 'Your will be done' isn't giving up—it's growing up. It's acknowledging that God sees things you can't see, knows things you don't know, is working in ways you can't perceive.

The silence isn't abandonment. Sometimes God's silence is His presence in a different form—a form that doesn't feel like presence, but is. Keep showing up. Keep bringing your prayers. Let today's verse sustain you in the waiting.`,
    application: [
      "Keep praying, but examine what you're praying for. Are you demanding outcomes, or seeking relationship regardless of outcomes?",
      "Look for answers you might be missing. Sometimes God says yes to something you weren't even asking. Sometimes the answer is unexpected.",
      "'Your will be done' isn't resignation. It's trust. It's acknowledging that God sees what you can't. Practice saying it and meaning it.",
      "Stay connected to others who pray. Unanswered prayer is heavy. Let the community carry it with you."
    ]
  },

  "Finding My Purpose": {
    title: "For Those Seeking Purpose",
    content: `'What's my purpose?' is the question of our age. Everyone else seems to have it figured out—clear calling, obvious direction, meaningful work. You're still searching. Today's Scripture enters that search.

Here's the truth: Scripture doesn't usually reveal purpose through dramatic signs or clear roadmaps. Purpose emerges through faithfulness. The person who's faithful in small things begins to see the larger pattern. The one who engages God's Word daily begins to hear what they're being called toward.

Today's verse isn't a career aptitude test. But it shapes the kind of person who discovers purpose. Scripture forms character, clarifies values, develops wisdom. Purpose flows from who you are, not just what you do. And who you are is shaped by the Word.

Stop searching so frantically. The desperate pursuit of purpose is often just anxiety wearing a spiritual mask. What if you already have a purpose—knowing and loving God—and everything else is application? What if the search is distracting you from the thing that would reveal the answer?

Faithfulness reveals calling. Be faithful with today—this verse, this prayer, this act of obedience—and trust that purpose will emerge. It usually does, but rarely on our timeline.`,
    application: [
      "Replace 'What's my purpose?' with 'What does today's verse call me to be?' Who before what. Character before career.",
      "Take the next faithful step you CAN see. Purpose emerges through action, not endless contemplation.",
      "Serve somewhere while you're searching. Get involved. Do something. Waiting for clarity before acting keeps you stuck.",
      "Ask people who know you well what they see in you. Sometimes others see gifts we're blind to. Let the community speak into your purpose."
    ]
  },

  "Struggling to Forgive": {
    title: "For Those Struggling to Forgive",
    content: `Someone hurt you deeply, and forgiveness feels impossible. Every time you think you've let it go, the memory returns, and so does the anger. The wound is real. The damage was real. Today's Scripture speaks into that stuck place.

Here's the truth: you can't manufacture forgiveness through willpower. You've probably tried. It doesn't work. Real forgiveness flows from somewhere deeper—from being forgiven ourselves, from receiving grace, from letting God's love heal what our effort can't.

Today's verse doesn't minimize what was done to you. Forgiveness isn't saying the wound didn't matter or the damage wasn't real. It's releasing the person to God's judgment instead of your own. It's refusing to let unforgiveness poison your own soul.

Unforgiveness feels like a weapon against the person who hurt you. But they rarely feel the weight of your resentment—you do. Every day. Until you let it go. The bitterness you're holding isn't punishing them. It's punishing you.

Start with willingness. 'Lord, I'm not ready to forgive, but I'm willing to become willing.' That's an honest prayer. That's where healing begins. Today's verse gives you something to cling to while you work toward release.`,
    application: [
      "Spend time considering how much YOU'VE been forgiven. Let that reality soak in. Forgiveness flows from receiving, not achieving.",
      "Start with willingness: 'Lord, I'm not ready to forgive, but I'm willing to become willing.' That's honest. He can work with that.",
      "Forgiveness is often a process, not a moment. You might have to forgive the same offense many times. Keep returning to Scripture.",
      "Distinguish forgiveness from trust. You can forgive and still have boundaries. Forgiveness doesn't mean pretending it didn't happen."
    ]
  },

  "New Believer": {
    title: "For New Believers",
    content: `Welcome. Everything is new—the language, the practices, the community, the expectations. You're learning to live differently, and sometimes you're not sure you're doing it right. Today's Scripture is part of your new foundation.

Here's what you need to know: you didn't earn your place. You didn't clean yourself up enough to be accepted. You received grace—freely, undeservedly, amazingly. Today's verse is part of a story you've just entered, a story that's been true for thousands of years and is now true for you.

You're going to mess up. That's okay—everyone does. What matters is what you do when you mess up. The Scripture you're beginning to learn will tell you: come back. Return. Confess. Receive grace again. You're not disqualified by failure. You're held by love.

Learn the basic practices that help faith grow: regular time in Scripture, honest prayer, consistent community with other believers. These aren't boxes to check to earn God's approval—you already have His approval. They're how you grow. They're how today's verse gets worked into your life.

Don't compare yourself to people who've been doing this for decades. They've had more time. Your job is to be faithful today—to engage with this verse, to talk to God honestly, to show up tomorrow and do it again. That's how faith grows.`,
    application: [
      "Establish basic rhythms: daily Scripture reading (start simple), honest prayer, weekly church. You're building a foundation.",
      "Find a mentor—an older believer who can answer your questions. You need someone further along the journey.",
      "Don't clean yourself up before coming to God. Come as you are. That's how grace works.",
      "When you fail, run TO God, not FROM God. That's the difference between growing and getting stuck."
    ]
  }
}
